{
  "doc_id": "27957",
  "text": "There are also numerous reports of negative effects of dietary saponins. Dietary saponins depressed growth, feed consumption in gerbils and egg production in poultry [CITATION_1] Terapunduwat & Tasaki, 1986; [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . These negative effects have been ascribed to several properties of saponins such as reduced feed intake caused by the astringent and irritating taste of saponins (see [CITATION_4] , reduction in intestinal motility [CITATION_5] , reduction in protein digestibility [CITATION_6] ) and damage to the intestinal membrane and inhibition of nutrient transport described earlier in the present review. Production of active metabolites (see [CITATION_7] ) by hydrolysis of saponins by intestinal bacteria [CITATION_8] ) also needs to be considered. More investigations are required into the fate of ingested saponins in the digestive tract of ruminants and single-stomached animals.",
